{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":564,"text":"My students and I\nwork on very tiny robots."},{"time":4209,"text":"Now, you can think of these\nas robotic versions"},{"time":6426,"text":"of something that you're all\nvery familiar with: an ant."},{"time":10016,"text":"We all know that ants\nand other insects at this size scale"},{"time":12776,"text":"can do some pretty incredible things."},{"time":15012,"text":"We've all seen a group of ants,\nor some version of that,"},{"time":18197,"text":"carting off your potato chip\nat a picnic, for example."}]},{"cues":[{"time":22467,"text":"But what are the real challenges\nof engineering these ants?"},{"time":25910,"text":"Well, first of all, how do we get\nthe capabilities of an ant"},{"time":29861,"text":"in a robot at the same size scale?"},{"time":31909,"text":"Well, first we need to figure out\nhow to make them move"},{"time":34513,"text":"when they're so small."},{"time":35923,"text":"We need mechanisms like legs\nand efficient motors"},{"time":38223,"text":"in order to support that locomotion,"},{"time":40072,"text":"and we need the sensors,\npower and control"},{"time":42563,"text":"in order to pull everything together\nin a semi-intelligent ant robot."},{"time":46525,"text":"And finally, to make\nthese things really functional,"},{"time":49071,"text":"we want a lot of them working together\nin order to do bigger things."}]},{"cues":[{"time":53019,"text":"So I'll start with mobility."},{"time":55710,"text":"Insects move around amazingly well."},{"time":58871,"text":"This video is from UC Berkeley."},{"time":60559,"text":"It shows a cockroach moving\nover incredibly rough terrain"},{"time":63342,"text":"without tipping over,"},{"time":65195,"text":"and it's able to do this because its legs\nare a combination of rigid materials,"},{"time":69192,"text":"which is what we traditionally\nuse to make robots,"},{"time":71545,"text":"and soft materials."},{"time":74374,"text":"Jumping is another really interesting way\nto get around when you're very small."},{"time":78201,"text":"So these insects store energy in a spring\nand release that really quickly"},{"time":82270,"text":"to get the high power they need\nto jump out of water, for example."}]},{"cues":[{"time":86281,"text":"So one of the big\ncontributions from my lab"},{"time":89403,"text":"has been to combine\nrigid and soft materials"},{"time":92153,"text":"in very, very small mechanisms."},{"time":94367,"text":"So this jumping mechanism\nis about four millimeters on a side,"},{"time":97532,"text":"so really tiny."},{"time":99220,"text":"The hard material here is silicon,\nand the soft material is silicone rubber."},{"time":103058,"text":"And the basic idea is that\nwe're going to compress this,"},{"time":105953,"text":"store energy in the springs,\nand then release it to jump."},{"time":108654,"text":"So there's no motors\non board this right now, no power."},{"time":112037,"text":"This is actuated with a method\nthat we call in my lab"},{"time":114800,"text":"\"graduate student with tweezers.\"\n(Laughter)"},{"time":117472,"text":"So what you'll see in the next video"},{"time":119306,"text":"is this guy doing\namazingly well for its jumps."},{"time":122333,"text":"So this is Aaron, the graduate student\nin question, with the tweezers,"},{"time":125947,"text":"and what you see is this \nfour-millimeter-sized mechanism"},{"time":128630,"text":"jumping almost 40 centimeters high."},{"time":130841,"text":"That's almost 100 times its own length."},{"time":133265,"text":"And it survives, bounces on the table,"},{"time":135221,"text":"it's incredibly robust, and of course\nsurvives quite well until we lose it"},{"time":138735,"text":"because it's very tiny."}]},{"cues":[{"time":141361,"text":"Ultimately, though, we want\nto add motors to this too,"},{"time":143970,"text":"and we have students in the lab\nworking on millimeter-sized motors"},{"time":147086,"text":"to eventually integrate onto\nsmall, autonomous robots."},{"time":150686,"text":"But in order to look at mobility and\nlocomotion at this size scale to start,"},{"time":154267,"text":"we're cheating and using magnets."},{"time":156241,"text":"So this shows what would eventually\nbe part of a micro-robot leg,"},{"time":159317,"text":"and you can see the silicone rubber joints"},{"time":161334,"text":"and there's an embedded magnet\nthat's being moved around"},{"time":163963,"text":"by an external magnetic field."}]},{"cues":[{"time":166266,"text":"So this leads to the robot\nthat I showed you earlier."},{"time":169959,"text":"The really interesting thing\nthat this robot can help us figure out"},{"time":173110,"text":"is how insects move at this scale."},{"time":175117,"text":"We have a really good model\nfor how everything"},{"time":177342,"text":"from a cockroach up to an elephant moves."},{"time":179304,"text":"We all move in this \nkind of bouncy way when we run."},{"time":182228,"text":"But when I'm really small, \nthe forces between my feet and the ground"},{"time":186513,"text":"are going to affect my locomotion\na lot more than my mass,"},{"time":189288,"text":"which is what causes that bouncy motion."},{"time":191642,"text":"So this guy doesn't work quite yet,"},{"time":193317,"text":"but we do have slightly larger versions\nthat do run around."},{"time":196392,"text":"So this is about a centimeter cubed,\na centimeter on a side, so very tiny,"},{"time":200277,"text":"and we've gotten this to run\nabout 10 body lengths per second,"},{"time":203179,"text":"so 10 centimeters per second."},{"time":204565,"text":"It's pretty quick for a little, small guy,"},{"time":206598,"text":"and that's really only limited \nby our test setup."},{"time":208960,"text":"But this gives you some idea\nof how it works right now."},{"time":212027,"text":"We can also make 3D-printed versions \nof this that can climb over obstacles,"},{"time":215781,"text":"a lot like the cockroach\nthat you saw earlier."}]},{"cues":[{"time":219280,"text":"But ultimately we want to add\neverything onboard the robot."},{"time":222166,"text":"We want sensing, power, control,\nactuation all together,"},{"time":225859,"text":"and not everything\nneeds to be bio-inspired."},{"time":228765,"text":"So this robot's about\nthe size of a Tic Tac."},{"time":231900,"text":"And in this case, instead of magnets\nor muscles to move this around,"},{"time":235849,"text":"we use rockets."},{"time":238274,"text":"So this is a micro-fabricated\nenergetic material,"},{"time":240940,"text":"and we can create tiny pixels of this,"},{"time":243539,"text":"and we can put one of these pixels\non the belly of this robot,"},{"time":247326,"text":"and this robot, then, is going to jump\nwhen it senses an increase in light."}]},{"cues":[{"time":252645,"text":"So the next video is one of my favorites."},{"time":254618,"text":"So you have this 300-milligram robot"},{"time":257658,"text":"jumping about eight\ncentimeters in the air."},{"time":260064,"text":"It's only four by four\nby seven millimeters in size."},{"time":262974,"text":"And you'll see a big flash\nat the beginning"},{"time":265130,"text":"when the energetic is set off,"},{"time":266622,"text":"and the robot tumbling through the air."},{"time":268530,"text":"So there was that big flash,"},{"time":270139,"text":"and you can see the robot\njumping up through the air."},{"time":273336,"text":"So there's no tethers on this,\nno wires connecting to this."},{"time":276368,"text":"Everything is onboard,\nand it jumped in response"},{"time":278862,"text":"to the student just flicking on\na desk lamp next to it."}]},{"cues":[{"time":283243,"text":"So I think you can imagine\nall the cool things that we could do"},{"time":286897,"text":"with robots that can run and crawl\nand jump and roll at this size scale."},{"time":291604,"text":"Imagine the rubble that you get after \na natural disaster like an earthquake."},{"time":295394,"text":"Imagine these small robots\nrunning through that rubble"},{"time":297953,"text":"to look for survivors."},{"time":300171,"text":"Or imagine a lot of small robots\nrunning around a bridge"},{"time":303127,"text":"in order to inspect it\nand make sure it's safe"},{"time":305286,"text":"so you don't get collapses like this,"},{"time":307326,"text":"which happened outside of \nMinneapolis in 2007."},{"time":311233,"text":"Or just imagine what you could do"},{"time":312995,"text":"if you had robots that could\nswim through your blood."},{"time":315518,"text":"Right? \"Fantastic Voyage,\" Isaac Asimov."},{"time":317851,"text":"Or they could operate without having\nto cut you open in the first place."},{"time":322206,"text":"Or we could radically change\nthe way we build things"},{"time":324936,"text":"if we have our tiny robots\nwork the same way that termites do,"},{"time":328343,"text":"and they build these incredible\neight-meter-high mounds,"},{"time":331108,"text":"effectively well ventilated\napartment buildings for other termites"},{"time":335196,"text":"in Africa and Australia."}]},{"cues":[{"time":337287,"text":"So I think I've given you\nsome of the possibilities"},{"time":339717,"text":"of what we can do with these small robots."},{"time":342154,"text":"And we've made some advances so far,\nbut there's still a long way to go,"},{"time":346561,"text":"and hopefully some of you\ncan contribute to that destination."}]},{"cues":[{"time":349419,"text":"Thanks very much."}]},{"cues":[{"time":351187,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}